| The basics of oxygen therapy | Uses the case study to explain core prescribing concepts. Covers: 1. Oxygen as a prescribed medication 2. Defining dose (flow rate) vs. delivery 3. Target saturation ranges (SpO₂ vs ABG) 4. The therapeutic window. **Key message:** Oxygen therapy requires precise prescribing with clear dose and target parameters, mirroring standard pharmacological practice. | • Dose of oxygen is flow<br>• The greater the SpO2 saturation, the better | Text and accordion | Image one from hero image series in visual design brief; Image one from BTF observations in visual design brief | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Executive Summary; Section A: Recommended target saturation range 94–98%; Section A3: Target 88–92% for COPD; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 3; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Hypoxaemia and Oxygen as a Drug | LO1 | 1.00 – 1.30 |
| The role of clinical judgement in using oxygen therapy | Explores patient-specific target saturation ranges through clinical examples (e.g., pneumonia, COPD hypercapnia, paraquat poisoning). **Flipcard activity:** Identifying correct targets and rationales for diverse clinical profiles. **Key messages:** There is no universal target saturation; ranges must be tailored to the patient’s underlying pathology and physiological risks. | • Assuming a universal 92–96% target for all patients<br>• Treating SpO2 as a "higher is better" metric instead of understanding the physiological therapeutic window<br>• Aiming for 100% saturation in routine care, which risks hyperoxia and can mask clinical deterioration | Text and flip card images | Flip card with three random patient images appropriate to condition. See visual design brief for Flip card exercise. Note that images may be substituted for clinical scenario text if imagery is difficult to obtain. | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section G; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 3; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Physiological Effects of Hyperoxaemia (Table 1); Section: High FiO₂ and Hyperoxaemia Lead to Complex Respiratory Effects | LO1 | 1.30 – 2.00 |
| Oxygen as a prescribed medication: getting the dose right | Explains the relationship between flow rate, FiO₂, and dynamic dosing principles. Covers stepwise approach to initiating, adjusting, and weaning based on SpO₂ response. Addresses inspiratory flow demand and device selection principles. **Key message:** Oxygen dose must be actively titrated to patient response, not treated as a static setting. | • Equating flow rate (L/min) with delivered dose (FiO₂)<br>• Not titrating 'dose' to reflect response of SpO₂ numbers | Quote block, List, Timeline:<br>1. **Initial SpO₂ < 92%** → (Step 1)<br>2. **SpO₂ declining** → Small increase to see if SpO₂ improves (Step 2)<br>3. **SpO₂ > 94% stable** → Opportunity to wean (Step 3)<br>4. **SpO₂ maintained on room air** → Weaning from oxygen | See visual design brief | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section S: Prescribing Oxygen Therapy; Section T: Monitoring and Adjusting Oxygen Therapy; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 2; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Titration of Oxygen Therapy to Target Arterial Oxygen Saturation Range | LO2 | 1.30 – 2.00 |

