| Screen title | Screen content | Variations / common mistakes to focus on | Screen type | Media required | Resources required / consultation | Learning outcome/s addressed | Seat time |
|-------------|---------------|------------------------------------------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------------|-----------------------------|-----------|
| Joe's story continued - Hidden signs of respiratory deterioration | Case vignette demonstrating how normal saturation can mask increased work of breathing and early deterioration. **Hotspot activity:** Identifying key physical signs of respiratory effort on the patient image. **Key message:** Pulse oximetry is only one metric; clinical observation of respiratory effort remains critical for early escalation. | • Over-reliance on pulse oximetry as a standalone metric<br>• Delaying escalation when respiratory effort increases despite normal saturations | Text in same format as previous scenarios | Image of Joe (similar to reference image) but labelled graphic (block is NSW Hotspot interaction). See visual design brief: Physical signs of respiratory effort | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section B: Clinical and Laboratory Assessment; Section B3: Use of NEWS track and trigger system; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 1; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Delayed Recognition of Deterioration | LO1 | 1.00 – 1.30 |
| Understanding what we are observing in oxygen therapy | Details limitations of pulse oximetry and explains complementary measures (SaO₂ vs. SpO₂, PaCO₂, ABG implications). Covers when clinical signs diverge from oximetry readings and the role of targeted blood gases. **Key message:** Normal SpO₂ does not guarantee adequate tissue oxygenation; clinicians must integrate clinical observation with targeted blood gases when deterioration is suspected. | • Assuming normal SpO₂ guarantees adequate tissue oxygenation<br>• Delaying ABG when clinical signs diverge from oximetry<br>• Misinterpreting venous gas PaCO₂ (if obtained) as equivalent to arterial values<br>• Not recognising V/Q mismatch (in Joe due to pneumonia decreasing perfusion) | Text, Accordion interaction with headings | Not applicable as there may be variation with iView and EPIC for recording respiratory values outside of BTF | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section C: Arterial and Capillary Blood Gases; Section B: Clinical and Laboratory Assessment; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 1; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Pulse Oximetry Limitations | LO4 | 1.30 – 2.00 |
| When oxygen therapy can cause harm | Explores pathways of oxygen-induced harm. Covers: 1. Hyperoxaemia risks 2. Rebreathing and V/Q mismatch 3. Hypercapnic respiratory failure mechanisms. **Tab interaction:** Matching clinical scenarios to appropriate intervention pathways (e.g., NIV escalation). **Key messages:** Unmonitored oxygen escalation can trigger physiological deterioration; recognizing harm pathways guides timely intervention. | • Overlooking subtle hypercapnic signs<br>• Escalating flow without reassessing ventilation/rebreathing risk or checking for oxygen creep | Tab interaction - Segments three distinct risk patterns. Follow with mini-vignettes on how oxygen should be used in each case (i.e progression to NIV for hypercapnia, etc). | n/a | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section L: Mixtures of Oxygen with Other Gases; Section H: Oxygen Use in Perioperative Care; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 3; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Hyperoxaemia and High Inspired Oxygen Concentrations; Section: Physiological Effects of Hyperoxaemia (Table 1) | LO1 | 1.30 – 2.00 |

