### Topic: Principles of titration

| Screen title | Screen content | Variations / common mistakes to focus on | Screen type | Media required | Resources required / consultation | Learning outcome/s addressed | Seat time |
|-------------|---------------|------------------------------------------|-------------|---------------|----------------------------------|-----------------------------|-----------|
| Joe's story continued – No improvement despite oxygen | Case scenario demonstrating persistent hypoxaemia despite initial oxygen therapy. Introduces systematic troubleshooting and the concept of stepwise titration when baseline response is inadequate. **Key message:** Lack of improvement requires systematic equipment verification before dose escalation. | Understanding concept of titration if patient isn't responsive to oxygen | Text with image | "Joe" with oxygen mask; BTF obs showing RR, HR and SpO2 (plus BP, temp) trend fifteen minutes later. See visual design brief. | 7.1.2 Value and limitations of pulse oximetry, BTS (2017); O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 5: High FiO₂ to Achieve Target SpO₂ Indicates Serious Illness; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Delayed Recognition of Deterioration and Risks of Hyperoxaemia | LO3 | 1.00 – 1.30 |
| Why we titrate oxygen and how we start | Troubleshooting checklist prioritizing equipment and probe verification before increasing oxygen dose. Covers common artefacts (kinked tubing, poor seal, vasoconstriction) and when to escalate to ABG. **Key message:** Never escalate flow without first ruling out equipment failure and measurement artefacts. | • Jumping straight to titration and escalation without verifying equipment patency, seal, or probe placement<br>• Assuming static SpO₂ reflects true physiological decline when it may simply indicate a kinked tube, tube attachment to oxygen regulator instead of air, poor mask fit, or peripheral vasoconstriction artefacts | Table, Flip cards (KC/explore) true/false knowledge check - and to true to continue, nothing if properly checked that is impacting fraction of inspired oxygen delivered. If worried, ABG for better signalling. | Image of blocked/clear tube; Image of mispositioned nasal cannula within nares and then correctly positioned; Image of incorrectly placed and correctly placed oxygen probes; normal/vasoconstricted (Raynaud's disease) hands. See visual design brief. | 7.1.2 Value and limitations of pulse oximetry, BTS (2017); O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 5; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Delayed Recognition of Deterioration and Risks of Hyperoxaemia | LO4 | 1.00 – 1.30 |
| Titrating up and down | Reviews oxygen delivery devices and stepwise titration protocols. Covers incremental flow adjustments, mandatory observation windows, and escalation triggers for rapid SpO₂ drops. **Key message:** Titration requires measured, protocol-driven adjustments with consistent physiological monitoring. | • Making large, unmeasured flow jumps that overshoot target saturation<br>• Skipping the mandatory 5-minute physiological equilibrium window<br>• Failing to recognise that a ≥3% rapid drop overrides the standard wait time | Text, image carousel, multiple-choice single answer knowledge check | Image of each kind of device (nasal cannula low-flow and high flow), simple facemask (Hudson mask), Venturi mask (single colour and multicolour marked devices), high concentration reservoir mask, humidified high flow nasal cannula (both hNHF-O₂ / HFNC). Images should also be colours and labels as per reference link. May need to switch to hotspot graphic. See visual design brief. | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T: Monitoring and Adjusting Oxygen Therapy; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 4: Delivery (Nasal cannulae preferred); Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Titration of Oxygen Therapy to Target Arterial Oxygen Saturation Range | LO3 | 1.00 – 1.30 |
| What does the need to titrate tell us? | Scenario analysing "oxygen creep" to distinguish dosing adjustments from underlying disease progression. Highlights how rising FiO₂ requirements signal deteriorating V/Q matching. **Key message:** Increasing oxygen requirements reflects clinical deterioration, not treatment failure, and mandates prompt clinical review. | • Treating oxygen as a standalone treatment rather than a diagnostic indicator<br>• Escalating flow repeatedly without recognising that oxygen creep signals clinical deterioration and disease progression, not therapeutic failure | Texts and interactive hotspot graphic | Interactive hotspot over graph of SpO2, ventilation and perfusion index. SpO2 is constant, ventilation trending downwards. Hotspots show increasing dose of oxygen with device specs as well as giving V/Q ratio that worsens over time. See visual design brief. | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 5: High FiO₂ to Achieve Target SpO₂ Indicates Serious Illness; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Delayed Recognition of Deterioration and Risks of Hyperoxaemia | LO3, LO4 | 0.30 – 0.50 |
| Use of high flow oxygen | Explains the shift in therapeutic paradigm when escalating to high-flow systems. Covers: 1. Separation of flow rate and FiO₂ delivery 2. Active respiratory support benefits 3. Humidification and patient comfort. **Key message:** High-flow oxygen is a form of active respiratory support requiring distinct clinical monitoring and documentation. | • HFNC is not just an oxygen delivery system—it is a form of active respiratory support as well as delivering oxygen<br>• Not separating FiO2 delivery from flow rates | Text, Note block | Not applicable (high flow oxygen devices shown previously) | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 5; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Delayed Recognition of Deterioration and Risks of Hyperoxaemia | LO3 | 0.30 – 0.50 |
| Planning to wean: what failure to wean tells you | Weaning scenario identifying signs of unresolved respiratory pathology when patients fail step-down protocols. Covers pausing weaning cycles to reassess underlying V/Q physiology. **Key message:** Weaning failure is a clinical marker of unresolved pathology, not a titration error. | Mistaking weaning failure as inaccurate titrating rather than a marker of unresolved pathology | Texts and interactive hotspot graphic | Labelled graphic plots SpO₂, ventilation, and perfusion index (PI). Ventilation normalizes; PI remains stable. SpO₂ holds target through initial protocol step-downs, then drops once FiO₂ crosses lowest or 2nd lowest dose, unmasking a persistent shunt. Hotspots confirm protocol adherence, highlight the unresolved low V/Q physiology, and model pausing weaning to reassess rather than auto-escalating oxygen. See visual design brief. | O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 4: Delivery (Nasal cannulae preferred); Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Titration of Oxygen Therapy to Target Arterial Oxygen Saturation Range | LO3 | 0.30 – 0.50 |
| Monitoring and troubleshooting during oxygen therapy | Interaction distinguishing physiological tolerance from device efficacy during weaning. Covers separating patient comfort from physiological need and adjusting protocols accordingly. **Key message:** Stable SpO₂ alone does not confirm adequate weaning; clinical tolerance and physiological markers must align. | • Assuming stable SpO₂ justifies continuing a poorly tolerated or sub-minimum flow device<br>• Separating comfort from physiological need and not understanding tolerance/comfort may impact measurement accuracy | Text, Bullet list | n/a | O'Driscoll et al. (2017) BTS Guideline for Oxygen Use in Adults. Thorax; Barnett et al. (2022) TSANZ Position Statement on Acute Oxygen Use in Adults. Respirology; O'Driscoll et al., (2017) Section T; Barnett et al., (2022) Section 4; Beasley et al., (2019) Section: Titration of Oxygen Therapy to Target Arterial Oxygen Saturation Range | LO4 | 0.30 – 0.50 |

